    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-11-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-11-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="363"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d363">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.6212/62</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Attorney General</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cummings</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-11-17">November 17,
                            1934</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: Your communication dated
                    October 10, 1934 (Le 611.6212/56), enclosing a memorandum from the German
                    Embassy, dated September 22, 1934,<note n="44" xml:id="d363fn44">Letter of
                        October 10 not printed; for memorandum from the German Embassy, see <ref
                            target="#pg_444">p. 444</ref>.</note> with enclosures regarding an
                    exposition sponsored by the American Jewish Congress to be given in the Grand
                    Central Palace in New York City, was received and considered.</p>
                <p>For your information, this Department reached the conclusion that <pb facs="0556"
                        n="456" xml:id="pg_456"/> the mere holding of this exposition and the
                    provision in the exhibitors’ contracts requiring them to agree not to exhibit
                    any German merchandise did not furnish a basis for action by this Department
                    under the Federal antitrust laws.</p>
                <p>Very truly yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Homer Cummings</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
